const a = [
  {"id":3511,"text":"Diastolic heart failure in a 65-year-old man is predominantly due to which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 529.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertension","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral renal artery stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3514,"text":"A 4-year-old boy is brought by his parents with the complaint that he frequently catches a cold and gets cough. According to the parents, he had pneumonia thrice this year and had to be admitted to the hospital one time. On examination, an ejection systolic murmur is heard on the left upper sternal border with a fixed splitting of the second heart sound. The first heart sound is loud. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 298-299.","responses":[{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3538,"text":"What congenital defect is rubella most commonly associated with?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 77.","responses":[{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Teratology of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicuspid aortic valve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3669,"text":"Which of the following food items is rich in saturated fats?","explanation":null,"reference":"Forouhi NG, Krauss RM, Taubes G, Willett W. Dietary fat and cardiometabolic health: evidence, controversies, and consensus for guidance. The BMJ. Published June 13, 2018. Accessed June 18, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6053258/","responses":[{"text":"Spinach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Animal fat","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Yoghurt","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eggs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Canola oil","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3748,"text":"Concurrent administration of quinidine and digoxin results in drug-drug interaction. How does quinidine interact with digoxin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Bigger JT, Leahey EB. Quinidine and digoxin. An important interaction. Drugs. Published September 1982. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6751790","responses":[{"text":"Decreased the absorption of digoxin in GIT","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synergistic effect on myocardium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits the metabolism of digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased serum concentration of digoxin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antagonized the effect of digoxin on the A-V node","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3760,"text":"Suppurative pericarditis with subsequent scarring leads to which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 575. (2) Yacoub M, Quintanilla Rodriguez BS, Mahajan K. Constrictive-effusive pericarditis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 18, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519579/","responses":[{"text":"Adhesive mediastinopericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constrictive pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myopericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3762,"text":"A 50-year-old lady with a known case of rheumatoid arthritis for the last 15 years, develops lethargy, exertional dyspnea, collapsing radial pulse, visible nail bed, and carotid pulsation in the neck. On chest auscultation, high pitched early diastolic murmur is heard. What is the most likely valvular abnormality she is suffering from?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 300.","responses":[{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3809,"text":"Which of the following findings would indicate a high-risk factor prediction while performing the exercise tolerance test (ETT)?","explanation":"**ST-segment depression of 2 mm or more in inferior leads** during exercise tolerance testing is considered a strong indicator of myocardial ischemia and is a **high-risk factor for coronary artery disease**. This finding typically warrants further diagnostic investigations and possibly therapeutic interventions.\r\n\r\n\r\nA small drop in diastolic blood pressure is usually not considered a high-risk factor during ETT.\r\n\r\nUpsloping ST depressions are generally considered to be less specific for ischemia than horizontal or downsloping ST depressions.\r\n\r\nA drop in systolic BP could be concerning, but a 5 mm Hg drop is usually not considered a high-risk feature.\r\n\r\n ST elevation can be a concerning sign, but it usually needs to be evaluated in the context of other clinical and ECG findings. Isolated 1 mm ST elevation in V2-V6 without other corroborating evidence is not usually considered a high-risk factor prediction in ETT.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 449.","responses":[{"text":"5 mm Hg drop in systolic blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upsloping ST depression of 3 mm in V2-V6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 mm Hg drop in diastolic blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 mm ST elevation in V2-V6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 mm ST depression in inferior leads","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3866,"text":"Which of the following antihypertensives is safe to use in pregnancy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 214.","responses":[{"text":"Methyldopa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benazepril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metolazone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3871,"text":"Which of the following is correct about mitral valve prolapse?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 556.","responses":[{"text":"Is caused by congenital anomalies or degenerative myxomatous changes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Is associated with a variety of lethal arrhythmias","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Produces ejection click and early systolic murmur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Commonly associated with apical chest pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Is a condition associated with high risk of embolic stroke or TIA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3872,"text":"Stunned myocardium is a state of prolonged cardiac failure induced by short-term ischemia that usually recovers after several days of myocardial infarction. Which of the following statements best describe the myocardial stunning?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1)Vaidya Y, Cavanaugh SM, Dhamoon AS. Myocardial stunning and hibernation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537026/\r\n (2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 547.","responses":[{"text":"Refers to an area of systolic dysfunction due to chronic high grade coronary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is associated with Q waves on ECG corresponding to the area of systolic dysfunction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Refers to post ischemic systolic dysfunction can be expected to reverse immediately upon restoration of coronary perfusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Refers to systolic dysfunction in an area of nonviable myocardium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a prognostic marker used to assess the morbidity of myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3874,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding a typical second heart sound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Felner JM. The second heart sound. In: Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW, eds. Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations. 3rd ed. Butterworths; 1990. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK341/","responses":[{"text":"Quantifies pulmonary pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Best heard with the bell of stethoscope","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Best heard in 2nd left intercostal space","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normally it splits during inspiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps in diagnosis of atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3877,"text":"The dominant cause of ischemic heart disease (IHD) is insufficient coronary perfusion relative to which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 539.","responses":[{"text":"Progression of atherosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial demand","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Degree of vasospasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue hypoxia \u0026 pulmonary hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extent of thrombotic changes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3890,"text":"Which of the following is a side effect of angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors?","explanation":null,"reference":"Goyal A, Cusick AS, Thielemier B. Ace inhibitors. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 15, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430896/","responses":[{"text":"Agranulocytosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal artery stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3952,"text":"Which of the following blood vessels return blood from the body to the heart?","explanation":null,"reference":"About the heart and blood vessels - health encyclopedia - university of rochester medical center. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.urmc.rochester.edu/encyclopedia/content.aspx?ContentTypeID=90\u0026ContentID=P01761","responses":[{"text":"Left main coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta and pulmonary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta and superior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary artery and inferior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior vena cava and inferior vena cava","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3960,"text":"Rheumatic fever is an acute, immunologically mediated, multisystem inflammatory disease classically occurring a few weeks after an episode of pharyngitis. What will be the most likely infective agent of such a condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 557.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococci","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonococci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella typhi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3961,"text":"Peripheral cyanosis occurs in which of the following pathologies?","explanation":"**Low cardiac output** can result in **peripheral cyanosis** due to inadequate blood circulation, causing a lack of oxygen supply to the extremities. When the body's tissues and organs do not receive enough oxygen, they may exhibit a bluish color, known as cyanosis.\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCongenital heart diseases (right to left shunt condition would more likely result in central cyanosis, affecting areas like the lips and tongue, rather than peripheral cyanosis.\r\n\r\nPulmonary edema condition primarily affects lung function and would generally lead to central, not peripheral, cyanosis.\r\n\r\nPulmonary embolism would primarily affect lung function and would typically result in central, not peripheral, cyanosis.\r\n\r\nLung diseases would generally result in central cyanosis due to impaired gas exchange in the lungs, affecting the oxygen saturation of blood circulating to the central parts of the body.","reference":"Adeyinka A, Kondamudi NP. Cyanosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482247/","responses":[{"text":"Congenital heart diseases (right to left shunt)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low cardiac output","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung diseases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3963,"text":"The characteristic pathognomonic finding of fibrinous pericarditis is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 574.","responses":[{"text":"Pericardial friction rub","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ewart's sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardial effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardial knock","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3968,"text":"Fibrocalcific scarring in constrictive pericarditis disturbs cardiac function by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 575.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac dilatation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restriction of diastolic expansion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3975,"text":"Digitalis is used in a patient of atrial fibrillation because of the following reasons?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 242, 256.","responses":[{"text":"Increases the effective refractory period in AV node","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases the excitability of atria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolongs the repolarization in AV node","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases the atomicity of the atria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases the conductivity of AV node","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3978,"text":"Rhabdomyoma tumor when presents in heart, which syndrome is most likely to rule out as it is most frequently associated with this tumor?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1316, 1317.","responses":[{"text":"Turner syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberous sclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Klinefelter syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Down syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Li-Fraumeni syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3983,"text":"A 70-year-old male has abdominal pain with a mass. On angiography, the abdominal mass is revealed as an aneurysm of the aorta. The most likely cause is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 502.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trauma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atheroseclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syphilis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3984,"text":"For variant (Prinzmetal angina), which of the following drug would be most appropriate for long-term therapy aimed at reducing the incidence or severity of coronary vasospasm?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 263.\r\n\r\n2) Rodriguez Ziccardi M, Hatcher JD. Prinzmetal angina. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 22, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430776/","responses":[{"text":"Diltiazem","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroglycerin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3989,"text":"A young male drug abuser with a history of hepatitis (HBV), presents with hypertension, abdominal pain, melena, muscle aches, and skin nodules. The laboratory test confirms HbsAg and pANCA positivity. Which one of the following describes the histopathologic appearance of the vasculitis in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 509.","responses":[{"text":"Necrotizing and granulomatous inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transmural fibrous thickening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic medial degeneration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous inflammation with presence of giant cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Segmental transmural necrotizing inflammation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3990,"text":"Which of the following is a selective beta-1 agonist drug?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 83.","responses":[{"text":"Digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digitoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amrinone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dobutamine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3998,"text":"Oligemic lung fields on X-ray chest are seen in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"**Tetralogy of Fallot** is a congenital heart defect characterized by four anatomical abnormalities, including ventricular septal defect, pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, and an overriding aorta. Due to these abnormalities,, there is a decrease in the blood flow to the lungs, leading to **decreased vascularity** or **\"oligemic\"** lung fields on a chest X-ray.\r\n\r\nTricuspid regurgitation primarily affects the right atrium and right ventricle and does not typically cause oligemic lung fields on chest X-ray.\r\n\r\nAtrial septal defect results in a left-to-right shunt and would not be expected to produce oligemic lung fields.\r\n\r\nMitral stenosis mainly affects the left atrium and left ventricle and tends to cause pulmonary congestion, not oligemia.\r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect generally causes increased blood flow to the lungs due to a left-to-right shunt, which would not produce oligemic lung fields.","reference":"Weerakkody Y. Tetralogy of fallot | radiology reference article | radiopaedia. Org. Radiopaedia. doi:10.53347/rID-7356","responses":[{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3999,"text":"Which of the following is the mechanism of action of statins?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 290.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibiting conversion of HMG CoA to cholesterol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Binds with bile acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit the conversion of cholesterol in VLDL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit the metabolism of acetyl CoA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase the metabolism of cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4004,"text":"Which one of the following conditions does not produce a systolic murmur?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 460.","responses":[{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute severe mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tumor polyp","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe tricuspid regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4016,"text":"Which of the following drugs causes constipation as a characteristic side effect?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 213.","responses":[{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lidocaine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Verapamil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sacubitril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4026,"text":"In dilated cardiomyopathy, the left ventricular ejection fraction should be:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 565.","responses":[{"text":"45% to 95%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Equals to 30%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater than 40%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesser than 40%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"50% to 80%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4031,"text":"A 6-month old child was brought in an emergency with respiratory distress. On examination, he has a hypodynamic precordium, high volume pulses, and a heart rate of 180/min. He has a diastolic murmur at the right second intercostal space. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018; 460.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4036,"text":"Which of the statement is true regarding systolic heart failure?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 529.","responses":[{"text":"Left ventricle fail to relax during diastole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"There is insufficient ejection fraction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abnormally stiff left ventricle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"There is rapid onset pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mostly occurs in patients older than 65 years","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4042,"text":"Atrial fibrillation is a frequent complication of which of the following pathologies?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Ogunsua AA, Shaikh AY, Ahmed M, McManus DD. Atrial fibrillation and hypertension: mechanistic, epidemiologic, and treatment parallels. Methodist DeBakey Cardiovascular Journal. Published 2015. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4814009/ \r\n\r\n2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 471.","responses":[{"text":"Graves disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4049,"text":"Lidocaine, as an antiarrhythmic, produces what effect?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 252.","responses":[{"text":"Increased PR interval","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced action potential duration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased contractility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced abnormal automaticity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased action potential duration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4051,"text":"Which of the following is the gold standard test for diagnosing coronary artery disease?","explanation":"**Coronary angiography** is considered the gold standard for diagnosing **coronary artery disease (CAD)**. It involves the injection of contrast dye into the coronary arteries via a catheter, allowing for direct visualization of the vessels and any blockages or stenosis. This method is highly sensitive and specific and allows for both diagnostic and therapeutic interventions, such as angioplasty or stent placement.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAlthough cardiac magnetic resonance imaging provides valuable anatomical and functional data, it is generally not used as the primary diagnostic tool for CAD.\r\n\r\nExercise tolerance testing (ETT) is useful for risk stratification and evaluation of ischemia but is not as accurate or definitive as coronary angiography.\r\n\r\nStress echocardiography is used to assess for inducible ischemia, but lacks the specificity and sensitivity of coronary angiography.\r\n\r\nWhile cardiac CT can visualize coronary anatomy and assess for the presence of coronary artery calcium, it is not as sensitive or specific as coronary angiography for the detection of significant CAD.","reference":"Shahjehan RD, Bhutta BS. Coronary artery disease. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564304/","responses":[{"text":"Cardiac magnetic resonance imaging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stress echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary angiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"High-resolution CT-scanning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise tolerance testing (ETT)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4053,"text":"A term infant is born with a large ventricular septal defect (VSD). Which congenital heart disease is most commonly associated with VSD?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Teratology of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4070,"text":"Hyperkalemia shows what ECG finding?","explanation":null,"reference":"Simon LV, Hashmi MF, Farrell MW. Hyperkalemia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470284/","responses":[{"text":"T-wave inversion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ST segment elevation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Narrow QRS complex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wide QRS complex","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Long QT interval","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4082,"text":"Which is the most common organism responsible for infective endocarditis?","explanation":"Overall, the most common organism responsible for infective endocarditis is ***Staphylococcus aureus***. Over recent years, Staphylococcus aureus has emerged as the leading cause of infective endocarditis, partly due to the increased use of intravascular devices and the prevalence of healthcare-associated infections.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus viridans* was traditionally considered the most common cause, especially in cases associated with dental procedures leading to transient bacteremia; however, it is now more commonly associated with subacute forms of endocarditis.\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus epidermidis* is more commonly associated with prosthetic valve endocarditis.\r\n\r\n*Enterococcus* species are a significant cause of infective endocarditis, particularly in healthcare settings and among older adults, but they are not the most common overall.\r\n\r\n*H. influenzae* is a less common cause of infective endocarditis and is more typically associated with cases in children and before the widespread use of the H. influenzae type b (Hib) vaccine.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nP.S. Different sources appear to contradict each other regarding the most common causative organism, with many saying *Streptococcus viridans* is the most common cause overall. We've cited the latest edition of Davidson here that says, \"Over three-quarters of cases are caused by streptococci or staphylococci. Viridans streptococci, such as *Streptococcus mitis* and *Strep. sanguis*, which are commensals in the oral cavity, can enter the bloodstream on chewing or tooth-brushing, or at the time of dental treatment, and are common causes of subacute endocarditis (Box 16.94)... *Staph. aureus* has now overtaken streptococci as the most common cause of acute endocarditis.\"\r\n\r\nThe question doesn't specify whether it's acute or subacute so it's hard to predict what the examiner is looking for. Our suggested answer based on the available information is *Staph. aureus*, but we cannot be 100% sure as we don't know if the question meant acute or subacute.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 528.","responses":[{"text":"Entrococcus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H. Influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus viridans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4083,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of reversed splitting of second heart sound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Felner JM. The second heart sound. In: Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW, eds. Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations. 3rd ed. Butterworths; 1990. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK341/","responses":[{"text":"Ischemic heart disease with left ventricular failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left bundle branch block","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Systolic hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large aorta to pulmonary artery shunt","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe aortic out-flow obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4084,"text":"The exact spot where the QRS meets the ST-segment is known as:","explanation":null,"reference":"St segment - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/st-segment","responses":[{"text":"U-wave","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"QRS junction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osborne wave","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"S-point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"J-point","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4085,"text":"Morphologic features seen in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy are which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 569.","responses":[{"text":"Granulomatous inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myofiber disarray","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dense inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilatation of sarcomeres","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multinucleated giant cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4087,"text":"A 7-year-old child has a history of breathlessness on and off. On examination, he has pansystolic murmur in the mitral area. What is your diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 521.","responses":[{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4089,"text":"Renin is released in response to low sodium levels in which of the following locations?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 489.","responses":[{"text":"Loop of henle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal convoluted tubules (DCT)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerular afferent arterioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extracellular fluid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4090,"text":"The evidence of overweight as an increasing risk factor for coronary artery disease is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 448.","responses":[{"text":"Established","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insufficient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Probable","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Possible","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Insignificant","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4092,"text":"Angina pectoris is a symptom complex of ischemic heart disease. Which angina is also known as preinfarction angina?","explanation":null,"reference":"Braunwald E, Morrow DA. Unstable angina. Circulation. Published June 18, 2013. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/full/10.1161/circulationaha.113.001258","responses":[{"text":"Prinzmetal angina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typical angina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stable angina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variant angina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crescendo angina","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4094,"text":"Rheumatic fever is characterized by constellation of findings, one of which is neurological disorders. Which neurological disorder occurs in rheumatic fever?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 562.","responses":[{"text":"Huntington's chorea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alzheimer's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sydenham's chorea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tourette","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4096,"text":"A woman with a prosthetic heart valve is on warfarin. She is planning for pregnancy. What advice is necessary in this regard?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 280.","responses":[{"text":"Warfarin should be discontinued and vitamin K should be prescribed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin should be replaced with heparin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin should be replaced with aspirin at analgesic dose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All medications which affect blood should be discontinused","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin should be continued till 3rd trimester","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4097,"text":"A 45-year-old man presents to the clinic because of tingling or numbness in the hands along with pain in his extremities. He has a 20-pack year history of smoking and is finally diagnosed with vasculitis involving medium and small arteries with veins. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Buerger's disease**, also known as thromboangiitis obliterans, predominantly affects small and medium-sized arteries and veins. It is more commonly observed in **smokers** and is characterized by symptoms like tingling, numbness, and pain in the extremities.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGranulomatosis with polyangitis primarily involves the respiratory tract and kidneys and is less likely to present with symptoms in the extremities. \r\n\r\nChurg Strauss syndrome is associated with asthma and eosinophilia and mainly affects the lungs and skin. \r\n\r\nGiant cell arteritis usually affects older people and is commonly seen involving the temporal artery, presenting with symptoms like headaches and vision issues. \r\n\r\nPolyarteritis nodosa is a systemic form of vasculitis affecting multiple organs but is not specifically associated with smoking.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 512.","responses":[{"text":"Buerger's disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyarteritis nodosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Churg Strauss syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giant cell arteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatosis with polyangitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4098,"text":"The only symptom of infective endocarditis could be:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 560.","responses":[{"text":"Fever which persist for long time","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myalgia and arthragia not responding to analgesics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Easy fatigliability","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe headaches and chills","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nausea and vomiting for long time","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4099,"text":"According to modified Duke criteria which of the following options is included as major diagnostic criteria for infective endocarditis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 529.","responses":[{"text":"Mycotic aneurysm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Major arterial emboli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous drug abuser","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"New valvular regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pre disposing heart condition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4100,"text":"The pathologic mechanisms involved in dilated cardiomyopathy are:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 565,566.","responses":[{"text":"Excessive exercise and red meat consumption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol consumption and childbirth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoidosis and helminth infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug hypersensitivity and SLE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mutations in C- Mye gene","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4102,"text":"A term infant is born with a large ventricular septal defect. Which coronary heart disease is most commonly associated with ventricular septal defect?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Transposition of great vessel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of Aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4104,"text":"Pulmonary hypertension is most severe in which untreated valvular heart diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 517.","responses":[{"text":"Aortic insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral insufficency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4106,"text":"Which of the following is the hallmark feature of right sided heart failure?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 530.","responses":[{"text":"Pleural effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardial effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiomegaly on chest X ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ankle and pretibial edema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enlarged Right ventricle on echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4109,"text":"Which of the following can be used for the diagnosis of rheumatic fever?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 559.","responses":[{"text":"Arthralgia with prolonged PR fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthralgia only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carditis with arthralgia and fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthralgia with fever and raised ESR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthralgia with fever","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4111,"text":"A colorless, odorless volatile liquid that may acquire a yellowish tinge on exposure to air, with burning sour taste are the physical and chemical properties of which mineral acid?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 482.","responses":[{"text":"Oxalic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrochloric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphuric acid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4113,"text":"A 2-year-old boy is admitted with complaints of breathlessness, easy fatigue, and failure to thrive. General physical examination shows cyanosis. The suspected diagnosis is congenital heart disease. What is the investigation of choice for diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 451.","responses":[{"text":"Angiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CBC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4114,"text":"Select which one of the following drugs is an inhibitor of ADP-induced platelet aggregation? \r\nSelect one:","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 273.","responses":[{"text":"Clopidogrel","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ticlopidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abciximab","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tirofiban","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4116,"text":"A 70-year-old woman came to the emergency with complaints of crushing pain in the sternal region associated with a rapid pulse, sweating, nausea, vomiting, and dyspnea. Her lab report shows elevated levels of cardiac-specific troponins T and I. What is the most appropriate medication given for additional pain management?","explanation":null,"reference":"Lu L, Liu M, Sun R, Zheng Y, Zhang P. Myocardial infarction: symptoms and treatments. Published July 2015. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25638347","responses":[{"text":"Paracetamol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buscopan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ibuprofen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroglycerin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4119,"text":"Which one of the following is true about the measurement of right-sided heart waves?","explanation":null,"reference":"Applefeld MM. The jugular venous pressure and pulse contour. In: Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW, eds. Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations. 3rd ed. Butterworths; 1990. Accessed June 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK300/","responses":[{"text":"A, C and V are positive deflection in jugular wave form","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Y decent becomes more prominent in tamponade and tricuspid stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The a waves is usually present in case of atrial fibrillation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The Y descent reflect fall in RA pressure after a waves peak","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of cannon 2 waves in patient wide complex tachycardia identify as ventricular origin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4121,"text":"A 2-year-old boy is brought to the hospital by his mother. She complains that her child seems breathless, gets tired easily, and is failing to thrive. The suspected diagnosis is congenital heart disease. Which of the following genetic syndromes is most commonly associated with congenital heart disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 533.","responses":[{"text":"DiGeorge syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Noonan's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Turner's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Down syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"William's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4122,"text":"Regarding acute coronary syndrome (ACS), which of the following is correct?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"In patients with unstable angina, aspirin is not needed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statins have no significant role in reduction of mortality in patients with ACS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In patients with non ST elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI), thrombotic therapy can be given","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It encompasses unstable angina, myocardial infarction and stable angina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin 75-325 mg/day improves survival with a 25% relative risk reduction in mortality","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4124,"text":"Cardiomyopathy is a heart disease resulting from a primary abnormality in the myocardium. Which cardiomyopathy is having 100% genetic causes?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomypathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertensive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4125,"text":"A woman has been prophylactically prescribed transdermal (skin patch) nitroglycerin. She uses it 24/7, except for a few minutes each day when she showers. What is the main concern with this \"around the clock\" administration?","explanation":null,"reference":"Klemsdal TO, Gjesdal K. Intermittent or continuous transdermal nitroglycerin: still an issue, or is the case closed? Cardiovascular Drugs and Therapy. Published March 1996. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8723164/","responses":[{"text":"Gradual development of reflex bradycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Onset of delayed, adverse responses including thrombosis and thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrous oxide poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Development of tolerance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Paradoxical vasoconstriction leading to hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4126,"text":"In which of the following conditions does inward movement of the apex beat during systole occurs?","explanation":null,"reference":"Niimi N, Mori N. Seesaw‐like movement of the chest wall. Clinical Case Reports. Published March 12, 2018. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5930187/","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular aneurysm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4127,"text":"A 50-year-old female, known case of rheumatoid arthritis for the last 15 years, develops lethargy, exertional dyspnea, collapsing radial pulse, visible nail bed \u0026 carotid pulsations in the neck. On auscultation of the chest, a high-pitched early diastolic murmur is audible. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 524.","responses":[{"text":"Endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral valve stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral valve prolapse","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4128,"text":"Unstable or crescendo angina initially presented as chest pain occurring at:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 540.","responses":[{"text":"Rest","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Night","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physical exertion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low physical activity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frequent intervals","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4130,"text":"Which one of the following is true about diastolic heart sounds?","explanation":"Mitral stenosis usually results in a **diastolic murmur** that is heard best at the apex of the heart. This murmur is often described as a long or **holodiastolic rumbling** and is indicative of severe mitral stenosis. It is often best heard in the left lateral decubitus position with the bell of the stethoscope.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nTricuspid regurgitation actually produces a pansystolic murmur rather than a holodiastolic one, typically heard best at the left lower sternal border. Acute severe aortic regurgitation (AR) usually produces an early diastolic decrescendo murmur, not a late diastolic murmur. Mitral valve prolapse (MVP) is usually associated with a midsystolic click and a late systolic murmur rather than a diastolic murmur. Tricuspid stenosis does indeed produce a diastolic murmur; it is a diastolic rumbling murmur heard best in the left lower sternal border and increases in intensity during inspiration.","reference":"Penman, Ian D., et al. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed., Elsevier, 2022: 460, 518-519.","responses":[{"text":"Acute severe AR produce late diastolic murmur at apex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid stenosis does not produce any diastolic sounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MVP usually produces early diastolic murmur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation produce holodiastolic murmur at 4th intercostal space","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A long or holodiastolic rumbling is indicative of severe mitral stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4131,"text":"Histologically, hypertension is associated with thickening of the arteriolar wall caused by?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 491.","responses":[{"text":"Oxidant damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β-adrenergic mediators","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tau protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline deposits","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4133,"text":"A 10-year-old female child weighing 30 kg is brought to the emergency department with complaints of migratory type of polyarthritis for the last 2 weeks. On examination, there is a grade 3/6 pansystolic murmur heard over the mitral area radiating towards the axilla. The most likely diagnosis is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 559.","responses":[{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infective endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatoid arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4140,"text":"Which of the following is a medium vessel vasculitis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 506.","responses":[{"text":"Kawasaki disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Microscopic polyangiitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Takayasu arteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giant cell arteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Churg - Strauss syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4142,"text":"A 42-year-old man comes to the emergency department with a history of taking liquids for suicide purpose. His pulse rate is 92/min and blood pressure is 120 /70 mmhg. He also has ulceration around the mouth and tongue. His chest is full of crepts and has severely labored breathing. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","explanation":"In a case of suspected poisoning leading to severe respiratory distress and potential airway compromise, the primary objective is to stabilize the patient's vital functions. This includes **establishing and maintaining the airway**, **supporting breathing**, and **ensuring adequate circulation** (often referred to as **ABCs**). These basic life-supporting measures are of utmost importance and take precedence over other treatment modalities. In a case like this, the patient may require intubation or other advanced airway management techniques, supplemental oxygen, and possibly intravenous fluids and medications to support blood pressure and heart function.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nMouth wash and antacids may be helpful for treating the ulcerations around the mouth and tongue but do not address the primary life-threatening issues of airway compromise and respiratory distress. Maintaining blood pressure is important but is part of the 'C' in ABC and should not take precedence over airway and breathing. Injection morphine could potentially worsen respiratory depression and is not appropriate in this context. Airway maintenance alone does not address the need for ensuring adequate breathing and circulation.","reference":"Thim T, Krarup NHV, Grove EL, Rohde CV, Løfgren B. Initial assessment and treatment with the airway, breathing, circulation, disability, exposure (ABCDE) approach. International Journal of General Medicine. Published January 31, 2012. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3273374/","responses":[{"text":"Airway, breathing and circulation establishment","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Injection morphine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway maintenance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mouth wash and antacids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood pressure maintenance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4146,"text":"Which type of atrial septal defect (ASD) is commonly associated with atrioventricular (AV) canal defect?","explanation":"**ASD primum** is commonly associated with **atrioventricular (AV) canal defects**. This is often seen in conditions like Down syndrome and is part of the spectrum of atrioventricular septal defects, which involve both the atrial and the ventricular septum as well as one or both of the AV valves.\r\n\r\nASD secundum is the most common type of ASD but is not specifically associated with AV canal defects. ASD sinus venosus and ASD coronary sinus are also specific types of ASD but are not commonly linked with AV canal defects.","reference":"Umapathi KK, Agasthi P. Atrioventricular canal defects. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557511/","responses":[{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD sinus venosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD primum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD secundum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD coronary sinus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4150,"text":"Which one of the following drugs lowers serum cholesterol by inhibiting the synthesis of cholesterol by blocking HMG-COA reductase?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 290.","responses":[{"text":"Gemfibrozil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotinic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lovastatin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Probucol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clofibrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4152,"text":"On autopsy, internal aspects of the stomach show brown folds and hardened esophagus. The acid involved will be:","explanation":null,"reference":"1. Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 487.\r\n2. Dow lecture slides: Cardiovascular module, Forensic slides, Topic: Corrosive poisoning 2","responses":[{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotinic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salicylic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxalic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4153,"text":"Which of the following best describes the apical impulse?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Normally distinct \u0026 localized at 5th intercostal space at left mid clavicular line and become hyperdynamic; displace downward/leftward in case of left ventricular hypertrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normally distinct \u0026 localized at left 4th intercostal space at mid clavicular line, become hyperdynamic with downward/ lateral shift in case of left ventricular enlargement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normally distinct \u0026 localized at left 4th intercostal space at mid clavicular line , become hyper dynamic; shift downward/ leftward in right ventricular hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normally distinct \u0026 localized at left 5th intercostal space lateral to mid clavicular line, become hyper dynamic at normal location in case of left ventricular enlargement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normally distinct \u0026 localized at right 4th intercostal space at mid clavicular line, shifted downward/right ward in case of right ventricular enlargement","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4155,"text":"Which of the following is an anti-hypertensive agent that acts by inhibiting the formation of angiotensin-II?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 210.","responses":[{"text":"Minoxidil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydralazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Captopril","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prazosin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4156,"text":"Gastric lavage is absolutely contraindicated in:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 474.","responses":[{"text":"Patient with strychnine poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When patient has poisoning with carbolic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When patient comes after four to six hours of poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient with volatile poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient with corrosive poisoning","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4157,"text":"A 25-year-old man complains of sharp pain which increases on lying down and is relieved with sitting. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"**Pericarditis** is characterized by sharp chest pain that often worsens when lying down and improves upon sitting up or leaning forward. This pattern is due to the inflammation of the pericardial sac surrounding the heart.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAortic dissection generally presents with severe, tearing pain that often radiates to the back. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) would be less likely to cause acute, sharp chest pain and is usually associated with long-term symptoms like shortness of breath and chronic cough. Both ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) and Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI) would cause ischemic chest pain but generally would not have pain characteristics that change with position. They would also likely have other symptoms such as radiating pain, sweating, and palpitations.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic dissection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4158,"text":"Para sternal lift or heave is present when:","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Right ventricular hypertrophy without right ventricular enlargement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricular hypertrophy with or without right ventricular enlargement","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left ventricular hypertrophy with or without left ventricular enlargement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"There is dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left ventricular enlargement with or without left ventricular hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4159,"text":"What is the commonest disease involving mitral valves?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 564.","responses":[{"text":"Left-ventricular hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital defects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syphilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic fever","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4160,"text":"Which one of the following is not correct regarding the measurement of jugular venous pressure?","explanation":null,"reference":"Jugular venous pressure - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/neuroscience/jugular-venous-pressure","responses":[{"text":"Either IJV or EJV can be used","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal jugular vein is preferred for JVP measurement as it is valued and direct communication with right atrium (RA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated EJV also may signify persistence left side JVC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jugular venous pressure gives bed side information about the volume status of patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"JVP is usually taken by asking the patient to lie down on the bed at 45°","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4161,"text":"Kussmaul's sign is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Johnson SK, Naidu RK, Ostopowicz RC, et al. Adolf Kussmaul: distinguished clinician and medical pioneer. Clinical Medicine \u0026 Research. Published September 2009. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2757428/","responses":[{"text":"Increase in heart rate when jugular veins are distended","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck veins collapse during inspiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilatation of pupil on deep inspiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pallor and coldness of fingers \u0026 toes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck veins may became more distended during inspiration","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4162,"text":"Acid neutralization within the stomach, in case of sulphuric acid ingestion, is contraindicated by which of the following?","explanation":"Acid neutralization within the stomach, in case of sulphuric acid ingestion, is contraindicated by **sodium bicarbonate**, when used to neutralize sulfuric acid, may produce excessive gas and result in gastric distension. This could increase the risk of gastric perforation.\r\n\r\nAluminum hydroxide gel, milk products, egg white, and milk of magnesia are generally used for acid neutralization in the stomach, although the effectiveness of these substances is not universally accepted for treating acid ingestion.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 484.","responses":[{"text":"Milk of magnesia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Egg white","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminum hydroxide gel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium bicarbonate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Milk products","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4163,"text":"In which of the following condition, there is left to right shunting of blood?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 533,534.","responses":[{"text":"Atrial septal defect (ASD)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessels (TGA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total anomalous pulmonary venous drainage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eisenmenger syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4165,"text":"Which of the following is one of the principal components of an atherosclerotic plaque?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 498.","responses":[{"text":"Amyloid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelioid cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous material","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Predominantly eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4166,"text":"For gastric lavage in an adult individual, the stomach wash tube should be passed up to:","explanation":null,"reference":"Vij K. Textbook of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology Principles and Practice. 5th ed. Elsevier; 2011: 450.","responses":[{"text":"35cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"40cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"50cm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"30cm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4167,"text":"Which one of the following antihypertensive groups is most likely to cause postural hypotension?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 93.","responses":[{"text":"Beta-one (β1) selective receptor blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ACE-inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arteriolar dilators","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-selective β-blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha (α)-receptor blockers","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4168,"text":"Which of the following conditions is characterized by normal plasma B type natriuretic peptide (BNP) levels?","explanation":"In **constrictive pericarditis**, the heart's ability to stretch and fill with blood is impaired due to a rigid pericardium. Despite this, the myocardium itself is not usually dysfunctional in the way it is in cardiomyopathies. **BNP** is typically released from **ventricular myocardium** under conditions of stress and stretch, which is less commonly seen in constrictive pericarditis compared to other listed conditions. Therefore, BNP levels are more likely to be normal in this case.\r\n---\r\n\r\nEndomyocardial arbitrative cardiomyopathy, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, dilated cardiomyopathy, and restrictive cardiomyopathy are conditions that affect the myocardium itself and are often associated with elevated BNP levels due to myocardial stress and stretch.","reference":"(1) Novack ML, Zevitz ME. Natriuretic peptide b type test. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556136/\r\n(2) Parakh N, Mehrotra S, Seth S, et al. NT pro B type natriuretic peptide levels in constrictive pericarditis and restrictive cardiomyopathy. Indian Heart Journal. Published 2015. Accessed June 26, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4382553/","responses":[{"text":"Constrictive pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endomyocardial arbitrative cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4169,"text":"A 45-year-old woman underwent mitral valve replacement by a prosthetic mechanical valve. What medication she is bound to use lifetime?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 279, 280.","responses":[{"text":"Digitalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coumarin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin receptor blockers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4170,"text":"An 8-year-old female child weighing 24 kg is brought to the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of jerky, involuntary purposeless, non-repetitive movements for the last 2 weeks. On examination, gait is irregular and there is deterioration in handwriting. There is also hypotonia and emotional disturbance. The most likely diagnosis is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 565, 1299.","responses":[{"text":"Wilsons disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral palsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Huntington chorea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Friedreich ataxia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4171,"text":"An elderly woman is given sublingual nitroglycerin for her effort-induced angina. The best mechanism for nitroglycerin is?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 263.","responses":[{"text":"Increases local synthesis \u0026 release of adenosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of cyanide ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockade of alpha adrenergic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases intracellular cGMP levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Selectively dilates/relaxes coronary arteries","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4172,"text":"Which one of the following tests (non-invasive) has the highest sensitivity in detecting coronary artery disease?","explanation":"**CT angiography** (computed tomography angiography) provides high-resolution images and is highly sensitive for detecting **coronary artery disease**. It allows visualization of coronary arteries and assessment of coronary artery disease with a high level of detail. It is especially useful for ruling out CAD in patients with low to intermediate risk.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nExercise tolerance test (ETT) is useful for risk stratification but not as sensitive as CT angiography for detecting CAD.\r\n\r\nStress echocardiography is useful for assessing functional impact but less sensitive than CT angiography.\r\n\r\nThallium scan is used in the assessment but not as sensitive as CT angiography.\r\n\r\nCardiac MRI is highly sensitive and specific but less commonly used than CT angiography due to cost and availability.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 452.","responses":[{"text":"Exercise tolerance test (ETT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thallium scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stress echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac MRI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT angiography","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4174,"text":"The use of angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors is contraindicated in:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Bilateral renal artery stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased renal function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperlipidemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4175,"text":"The most frequent congenital cardiac malformation is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4176,"text":"Which one of the following is correct regarding mitral stenosis (MS)?","explanation":"In **mitral stenosis**, the obstruction at the mitral valve causes turbulent flow across the valve during diastole, generating a **mid-diastolic rumbling murmur** that is best heard over the cardiac apex with the bell of the stethoscope.\r\n\r\nUsually, the symptoms of mitral stenosis occur when the mitral valve area reduces to about 1.5 cm^2 or less.\r\n\r\nMitral balloon valvotomy is not recommended for heavily calcified valves due to risk of complications.\r\n\r\nAntibiotic prophylaxis against infective endocarditis is only recommended in certain conditions or procedures.\r\n\r\nMS is commonly a result of rheumatic heart disease, although congenital forms do exist.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 460.","responses":[{"text":"It is mostly congenital in origin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral balloon valvotomy can be safely done in patients with heavily calcified mitral valve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Turbulent flow produces the characteristic low pitched mid diastolic murmur","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The patient remains asymptomatic until the valve area is less than 1 cm^2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotic prophylaxis against infective endocarditis is given to all patients","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4177,"text":"Which of the following factors has an association with congenital heart disease?","explanation":"Maternal infection with **rubella virus** during pregnancy, especially in the first trimester, can lead to a range of congenital abnormalities, including congenital heart disease in the newborn, i.e., **patent ductus arteriosus (PDA)**.\r\n\r\nThere is no established scientific evidence linking maternal tea consumption to congenital heart disease.\r\nOccupation: Occupation alone is generally not considered a risk factor for congenital heart disease.\r\nWhile maternal hypertension may have other adverse fetal effects, it is not directly associated with congenital heart diseases.\r\n\r\nWhile hypoxia can affect the fetus in multiple ways, it is not a known specific risk factor for congenital heart disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Occupation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Use of tea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rubella infection","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4178,"text":"A person in an emergency (ER) with a history of some unknown liquid ingestion requires gastric lavage. The ideal position of the patient while performing gastric lavage is?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 473.","responses":[{"text":"Fowler's position","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left lateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Supine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right lateral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4179,"text":"Which vascular tumor is seen in-patient with AIDS?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 518.","responses":[{"text":"Kaposi sarcoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomangioma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemangioendothelioma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemangiopericytoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacillary angiomatosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4181,"text":"The nutmeg liver in congestive cardiac failure has gross changes. Which of the following is the most likely correct answer?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Red brown periportal zone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red brown pericentral zone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pale yellow around central veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tan gray brown pericardial zone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red bluish areas in sinusoids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4182,"text":"A 10-year-old boy came to the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of pain in wrist and elbow joints along with pea-sized, palpable masses on extensor surface of forearm. He gave history of throat infection 3 weeks back. His lab tests show anemia, raised ESR and C-reactive protein. The diagnosis of this condition is based on which one of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 559.","responses":[{"text":"ASO titer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ESR levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jones criteria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ECG findings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Throat culture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4185,"text":"When a person dies suddenly from a heart attack, the most likely event that led to the sudden death is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 548, 549.","responses":[{"text":"Recline of the heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac arrhythmia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angina pectoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary artery embolism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4187,"text":"A 25-year-old patient with difficulty in breathing is diagnosed to have congestive heart failure. He is found to have differences in right and left arm pulses, diminished femoral pulses and notching of ribs on X-ray. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Coarctation of the aorta** is characterized by a narrowing of the aorta and would account for the symptoms of congestive heart failure, as well as the **differences in arm pulses, diminished femoral pulses**, and **rib notching on X-ray**.\r\n\r\nTransposition of great vessels typically causes cyanotic disease in the newborn period and is unlikely to present in this age group.\r\n\r\nMitral valve stenosis primarily affects the left heart and does not usually cause differences in arm pulses or diminished femoral pulses. \r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect would not lead to diminished femoral pulses or differences in right and left arm pulses. \r\n\r\nTetralogy of Fallot, a cyanotic congenital heart disease, would have been likely diagnosed much earlier in life and also does not typically present with rib notching or pulse differences between the arms.","reference":"1. Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 78.\r\n2. Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 509, 534.","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral valve stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4188,"text":"Rheumatic fever is an acute immunologically mediated multisystem inflammatory disease. Which organism is responsible for the pathogenesis of rheumatic fever?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 558.","responses":[{"text":"Klebsiella species","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rickettsia species","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coxsackie virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4192,"text":"The most common cause of hemorrhagic pericarditis is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 574.","responses":[{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bleeding diathesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant tumor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4194,"text":"Most cardiac-specific test in myocardial infarction is which one of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 550.","responses":[{"text":"BNP (plasma B natriuretic peptide)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CPK-MB enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CK enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac troponin I and T","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4198,"text":"Which of the following is a relative contraindication of exercise tolerance test (ETT)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 450.","responses":[{"text":"Aortic stenosis (severe)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Untreated severe systemic hypertension","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep vein thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Active myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4203,"text":"One of the important components of the renin-angiotensin axis is angiotensinogen, secreted by:","explanation":null,"reference":"Fountain JH, Lappin SL. Physiology, renin-angiotensin system. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470410/","responses":[{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4204,"text":"The primary action by which heparin prevents blood coagulation is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 276.","responses":[{"text":"Facilitation of anti thrombin III mediated inhibition of factor Xa \u0026 thrombin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of anti thrombin III to inhibit factor IX \u0026 XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct inhibition of prothrombin conversion to thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitation of antithrombin III mediated inhibition of factor XIIa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition by factor XII a \u0026 XIIIa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4206,"text":"Which of the following is used in severe hypertensive emergencies, is very short-acting, and must be given by intravenous infusion?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 514.","responses":[{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diazoxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroprusside","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydralazine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4223,"text":"Which one of the following cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk factors directly associated with nutrition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: CardioVascular-II module, Community Medicine slides, Topic: Role of Diet and Nutrition/ Lifestyle Modification.","responses":[{"text":"Stress","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gender","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Family history","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4224,"text":"Which of the following examination findings would most likely be seen in a patient with aortic stenosis?","explanation":"**Aortic stenosis** is characterized by a **diamond-shaped ejection murmur**. This type of murmur occurs during systole and is a **crescendo-decrescendo** type, typically loudest at the right second intercostal space or right upper sternal border and radiating to the carotid arteries. It often produces a palpable thrill. The murmur can actually become softer with increasing severity.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 522 (Fig 16.84).","responses":[{"text":"Diamond shaped ejection murmur","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intensity of murmur directly related to the severity of the lesion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No thrill","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extremely long decrescendo murmur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Murmur loudest along left sternal border","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4225,"text":"Select which one of the following antihypertensive drugs can be given safely in a pregnant woman?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 214.","responses":[{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prazosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methyldopa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4226,"text":"Which one of the following drugs is considered most effective in relieving and preventing the ischemic episode of variant angina?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Rodriguez Ziccardi M, Hatcher JD. Prinzmetal angina. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 22, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430776/\r\n\r\n2) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 263.","responses":[{"text":"Isosorbide nitrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroglycerine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diltiazem","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nifedipine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4227,"text":"Blood pressure regulation comprises two important functions. One is cardiac output and the other is following:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"EDGF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural factors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genetic factors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral resistance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental factor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4228,"text":"A 56-year-old patient died of sudden cardiac failure. An autopsy was performed and foamcells were noted in the histopathology section. Which primary cell converts into foam cells?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4229,"text":"A 50-year-old obese female complains about the shortness of breath after her trip to the USA. What is a possible diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sugerman HJ, Eklöf BG, Toff WD, Burke AE, Livingston EH. Air travel–related deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism. JAMA. Published December 19, 2012. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2012.4098","responses":[{"text":"Gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tension pneumothorax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4230,"text":"40-year-old unbooked multigravida came to labor room with term pregnancy having severe breathlessness and sign of cardiac failure. CBC show Hb 5.0gm/dl. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 566.","responses":[{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocarditis due to viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiamyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemchromatosis induced cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4231,"text":"Which one of the following is considered as the principal preventive population strategy for cardiac disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Yu E, Malik VS, Hu FB. Cardiovascular disease prevention by diet modification: jacc health promotion series. Journal of the American College of Cardiology. Published August 21, 2018. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6100800/","responses":[{"text":"Dietary \u0026 life style changes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Safe cigarettes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stress management","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adequate sleep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adequate physical activity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4232,"text":"Digoxin, their primary action on cardiac cell is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 256.","responses":[{"text":"Activation of slow Ca++ channel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of Na+/K+ ATPase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inactivation of Na+ channel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of the Na+/Cl- co-transporter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of adenyl-cyclase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4233,"text":"A 70-year-old man, diagnosed with coronary atherosclerosis came to cardiac OPD for routine follow-up. While waiting for his checkup he suddenly experienced angina. He was immediately given medication. What is the most appropriate medication given to relieve his pain?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 264.","responses":[{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zantac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroglycerin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ibuprofen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4234,"text":"Atrial septal defect is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 533-535.","responses":[{"text":"A congenital, cyanotic defect between left and right atrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An acquired defect of mitral valve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A congenital, non-cyanotic defect between left and right atrium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Defect between ascending aorta and pulmonary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A congenital, non-cyanotic defect between left and right ventricles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4235,"text":"Which one of the following has the greatest potential for the prevention of CVD?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Secondary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased physical activity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High risk strategy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population strategy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood pressure control","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4236,"text":"The main blood supply of the left side of the heart is by the left main coronary artery which gives rise to:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 525.","responses":[{"text":"Left anterior descending artery and posterior descending artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left anterior descending artery and coronary sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left anterior descending artery and circumflex artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obtuse marginal branch and posterior left ventricular artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4238,"text":"Which of the following adverse reactions is associated with ACE inhibitors?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 210.\r\n\r\n(2) Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 189.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Agranulocytosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hirsutism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4239,"text":"In heart failure which beta blocker is more beneficial?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bisoprolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoprolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carvedilol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4242,"text":"Which of the following is a common cause of sudden death:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4243,"text":"A 15-year-old boy was brought to the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of pain in knee and elbow joints along with pea-size palpable masses on the elbow. He gave a history of pharyngitis 2 weeks ago. His lab tests show anemia, raised ESR, and C-reactive protein. Which of the following is the most likely a diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 559.","responses":[{"text":"Typhoid Fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic Fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteomyelitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatoid arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septic arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4244,"text":"Select which one of the following hypolipidemic drugs when given orally, is neither absorbed nor metabolized in the intestine?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Probucol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholestyramine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gemfibrozil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lovastatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Finofibrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4245,"text":"A 40-year-old male case of increasing breathlessness, fatigue, and weakness for the last 2 months. He also has a history of radiation of mediastinum due to Hodgkin lymphoma 5 years ago. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocarditis due to viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemochromatosis induced cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4246,"text":"Which of the following conditions is characterized by a sustained apex impulse?","explanation":"In **aortic stenosis**, the apex impulse is often **sustained** due to the prolonged ejection of blood from the left ventricle, which is working harder to overcome the obstruction at the aortic valve.\r\n\r\nSustained apex impulse is not a feature typically seen in patent ductus arteriosus, Ventricular septal defects, hyperdynamic states, or mitral stenosis. In these conditions, other physical exam findings may be more prominent. For instance, hyperdynamic states usually present with a bounding pulse rather than a sustained apex impulse. Mitral stenosis would typically show a tapping apex due to the palpable first heart sound.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyper dynamic states","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4248,"text":"The commonest complication of large VSD is:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Double chamber right ventricle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary hypertension","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left ventricular dilation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial arrhythmias","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4249,"text":"10-year-old boy diagnosed case of beta-thalassemia major, on regular blood transfusion. came in E/R with signs and symptoms of heart failure. Investigations show Hb 8.0gm/dl, S. Ferritin 7000ng/ml. The echo shows dilated cardiomyopathy. What is the cause of cardiomyopathy?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Nutritiona anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood transfusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemochromatosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocarditis due to viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4250,"text":"Ebstein's anomaly may occur with:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Calcium channel blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ACE inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maternal benzodiazepine use","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium channel blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vit B12 deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4251,"text":"A 5-year-old child is referred for evaluation of suspected heart disease. On inspection of the precordium is hyperdynamic, while apex beat is felt in 6th intercostal space (I.C.S) lateral to the midclavicular line. The most probable cause of these findings is,","explanation":null,"reference":"Innes JA, Dover AR, Fairhurst K, Macleod J, eds. Macleod’s Clinical Examination. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 54-55.","responses":[{"text":"Left ventricular enlargement","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biventricular enlargement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricular hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricular enlargement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left ventricular hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4253,"text":"Most infarction of the apex of the heart (distal end of ventricles) are caused by occlusion of:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Left anterior descending","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left circumflex (LCA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Both right \u0026 left coronary arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4254,"text":"A newborn with respiratory distress has a continuous murmur at the 2nd left intercostal space. His apex beat is at the 6th intercostal space 2cm lateral to the midclavicular line. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4255,"text":"Select the pharmacological effects of statins besides their antihyperlipidemic activity?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Decrease stability of atherosclerotic lesions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased oxidative stress and vascular inflammation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevent embolic formation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-inflammatory and anti arrhythmic activity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight reduction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4256,"text":"A 2-year-old is brought to the pediatric outpatient department with complaints of breathlessness, easy fatigability, and failure to thrive. The suspected diagnosis is cyanotic heart disease. Which one of the following is a right-to-left shunt congenital heart disease?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4257,"text":"A 40-year-old female was found dead lying on the bed early morning. Her family took her for postmortem. The family told that she was not having any co-morbid and no known cardiac pathology. Later it was found that she died because of sudden cardiac death. Which one of the following is a non-atherosclerotic cause of sudden cardiac death in young people?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Subendocardial hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxidative stress","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypovolemic shock","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4258,"text":"Which of the following explains mitral valve prolapse (MVP)?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Is caused by congenital anomalies or degenerative myxomatous changes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Produces ejection click and early systolic murmur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Is associated with a variety of lethal arrhythmias","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Commonly associated with apical chest pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Is a condition associated with high risk of embolic stroke or TIA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4259,"text":"Name the anti-hypertensive agent that acts by inhibiting the formation of angiotensin-II?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Captopril","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydralazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minoxidil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prazosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proparanolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4270,"text":"A 28-year-old, male, known case of hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy, presented in the cardiac emergency room with a history of transient loss of consciousness. His elder brother had died at the age of 30 years. What will be your first line of treatment?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Beta blocker","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reassurance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol (non surgical) ablation of the septum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Implantable cardioverter defibrillator (ICD)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dual chamber pacing","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4271,"text":"A 10-year-old child presents to the clinic with complaints of palpitations. On examination, he has irregular radial pulses. He also has a discrepancy of heart rate at the apex (by auscultation) and radial pulse. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Heart block","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular fibrillation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac tamponade","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial fibrillation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sinus tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4272,"text":"A 35-year-old, female, a known case of chronic renal failure, presented to the outpatient department (OPD) complaining of shortness of breath. Her examination revealed apex beat obscured, heart sounds are muffled, and raised in jugular venous pressure (JVP) during inspiration. What is an appropriate investigation to diagnosis the condition?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"CXR PA view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum urea/creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ECG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac biomarker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4273,"text":"A 13-year-old girl came for a follow-up examination at the outpatient department (OPD) after 3 days hospital stay. She was diagnosed with Rheumatoid arthritis. What is the most predominant symptom in this condition?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Migratory arthritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sydenham chorea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythema marginatum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subcutaneous nodules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4274,"text":"Which is a false statement regarding surgical indication in aortic stenosis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"In symptomatic patients with aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In patients with severe aortic stenosis undergoing CABG surgery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In patient with moderate aortic stenosis undergoing CABG or surgery on the other valves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In patients with severe aortic stenosis undergoing surgery on the aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asymptomatic patients of aortic stenosis to prevent sudden cardiac death","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4275,"text":"In typical angina chest pain, probability of coronary artery disease:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"50%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"90%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"20%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4276,"text":"Commonest cause of death in myocardial infarction is:","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Left ventricular failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiogenic shock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial fibrillation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricular failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular fibrillation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4278,"text":"What is the most common indication for coronary artery bypass grafting?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Greater than or equal to 20% stenosis of right coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than or equal to 20% stenosis of left main stem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Poor ventricular function associated with multi-vessel disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than or equal to 50% stenosis of the proximal left anterior interventricular artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valvular heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10217,"text":"A female with a positive family history of diabetes comes to the office for screening for high blood sugar. What type of prevention is this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kisling LA, M Das J. Prevention strategies. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537222/","responses":[{"text":"Tertiary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primordial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quaternary","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10259,"text":"Which of these types of antidotes combine with poisons to form new less toxic compounds?","explanation":"**Chemical antidotes** work by chemically reacting with the poison to form a less toxic or non-toxic compound, thus **neutralizing** its harmful effects.\r\n\r\nPhysiological antidotes work by producing effects that are opposite to those of the poison but do not combine with the poison to form a new compound. Universal antidotes are general-purpose antidotes that can work against a variety of poisons but are generally not as effective as specific antidotes. Chelating agents bind to heavy metals in the body but do not form less toxic compounds with the poison. Physical antidotes work by adsorbing the poison or facilitating its elimination from the body without forming a new compound.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 475.","responses":[{"text":"Physiological antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical antidotes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Physical antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Universal antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chelating agents","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11868,"text":"How many seconds does a normal PR interval last?","explanation":"The normal **PR interval** on an electrocardiogram (ECG) lasts between **0.12 to 0.20 seconds**, which is equivalent to 120 to 200 milliseconds. A prolonged PR interval may suggest a first-degree atrioventricular (AV) block or other forms of conduction abnormality.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 448.","responses":[{"text":"0.30 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.22 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.20 sec","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0.32 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.28 sec","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14113,"text":"Which of the following can reduce the risk of sudden cardiac death in a patient with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Jameson JL, Fauci AS, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL, Loscalzo J, eds. Harrison’s Principles of Internal Medicine. 20th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 1795-1796.","responses":[{"text":"Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiofrequency ablation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β-Adrenergic blocking agents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular pacing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol septal ablation","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

